                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.419/68b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wheeler</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-12-08T13:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 8, 1923—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>370. British Chargé d’Affaires submitted on December 3 British draft liquor
                    treaty. Yesterday I handed British Chargé memorandum of proposed modifications.
                    It is apparent intent of Foreign Office to conclude the matter here, but if
                    questions should arise in your interviews you may say that modifications I have
                    suggested are deemed absolutely necessary. They do not affect substance. The
                    principal modification seeks to make it clear that provision relating to transit
                    through territorial waters of liquor and cargo under seal not destined for
                    delivery or consumption within the United States is to constitute exception from
                    penalty or forfeiture.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
